<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAM &amp; FLAG DESECRATION</font><br>
<tt>Wed May 28 12:38:25 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
My opposition to the Flag Desecration Amendment has everything to do with my military service during the Vietnam War.   The Vietnam War was just one of the many ways in which the government of the United States desecrated its own flag, as I alluded to in one of my earlier posts.  In its attempt to force the Vietnamese people to accept a government friendly to the US government and its powerful corporate allies, the Pentagon massacred over 2 million innocent Vietnamese civilians.  In so doing, they desecrated my flag and all that I was taught that it represented. <br><br>
 I have NEVER forgiven those bastards for giving so many of us 18 and 19-year-old young men of the time, the choice between participating in this criminal act in the name of &quot;patriotism,&quot; and dodging the draft through the use of student deferments, playing the ROTC runaround (cf. Bill Clinton), using connections to get safe spots in the National Guard or Army Reserve, or running like cowards to Canada or Sweden.<br><br>
This phoney amendment is yet another way for the flag-happy American know-nothings that started and prolonged, but in most cases evaded service in,  that war to suck us, once again in the name of patriotism, into  collaborating with their hidden agenda, which is no different than it was in Vietnam.   In more general terms, it can be expressed as follows:<br><br>
I am an American, and what's best for me ought to be good enough for everyone else.<br><br>
Earlier in our nation's history, this attitude was called &quot;Manifest Destiny,&quot; and it has been a well-spring of suffering for millions of innocent people here and abroad.<br><br>
By deifying the flag, these criminals will have a convenient and patriotic-looking symbol to disguise, and mute all criticism of, their pursuit of &quot;national&quot; interests that are gross violations of all the prinicples that we were all taught the flag stood for.<br><br>
The proposed Flag Desecration Amendment is another Vietnam.  It will divide this country just like the first one did.<br>
As veterans of the first, we have a chance, and I suggest the duty, to stop this from happening.<br><br>
John M. Stassi<br>
Vets For Free Speech<br>
&quot;The flag is a rag, nothing higher.  Liberty includes the right to set it on fire.&quot;<br><br>

